      "content": "While the search for third-party diplomatic evidence is a critical step, international justice bodies like the ICC currently lack the jurisdiction to adjudicate claims of historical boundary erasure unless it is part of a broader, sanctioned war crime context. Legal experts would frame such arguments through UN human rights mechanisms or as a diplomatic reparations case rather than a formal sovereignty claim, as the principle of *uti possidetis* still legally binds inherited borders even when they are claimed to be artificially drawn. Without a concrete, corroborated case involving active persecution or an ongoing genocide, tribunals will prioritize border stability and preventing conflict over overturning decades of established state fixing, regardless of the alleged \"historical wrong.\"",
